gene_function: ACTN3 (actinin alpha 3) is an actin-binding protein expressed in skeletal muscle that is involved in the ability of muscles to produce fast contractions.

ACE (angiotensin-converting enzyme) is a vasoconstrictor enzyme that is related to electrolyte balance and systemic blood pressure by causing blood vessels to constrict and blood pressure to increase. In athletic performance, it is related to cardiovascular and skeletal muscle function, fast twitch muscle activity, and muscle efficiency.

ADRB2/ADRB3 (adrenergic beta-2/beta-3 receptor) encode proteins in the family of beta adrenergic receptors which trigger agonist-stimulated adenylyl cyclase activity to divert blood flow to skeletal muscle. The beta-2-adrenergic receptor is responsible for increases in bronchodilation, ventricular function, and vasodilation, which impact the cardiovascular and pulmonary response to exercise. The beta-3-adrenergic receptor is involved in the regulation of lipolysis and thermogenesis.

ADRB2/ADRB3 (adrenergic beta-2/beta-3 receptor) encode proteins in the family of beta adrenergic receptors which trigger agonist-stimulated adenylyl cyclase activity to divert blood flow to skeletal muscle. The beta-2-adrenergic receptor is responsible for increases in bronchodilation, ventricular function, and vasodilation, which impact the cardiovascular and pulmonary response to exercise. The beta-3-adrenergic receptor is involved in the regulation of lipolysis and thermogenesis.

BDKRB2 (bradykinin receptor B2) is a receptor for the peptide bradykinin which causes blood vessels to enlarge (dilate) due to the relaxation of the muscular wall of the vessels, and causes blood pressure to decrease.

COL5A1 (collagen type V, alpha 1) is a member of group I collagen (fibrillar forming collagen) which is believed to regulate fibrillogenesis within tendons and other connective tissue. It is related to flexibility as a measure of athletic performance.

GNB3 (guanine nucleotide-binding protein subunit beta-3) is involved in transmembrane signaling systems and G protein activation of hormones, neurotransmitters, chemokines, and local mediators that may be conducive to athletic performance.
ACTN3 (actinin alpha 3) is an actin-binding protein expressed in skeletal muscle that is involved in the ability of muscles to produce fast contractions.

In athletic performance, it is related to cardiovascular and skeletal muscle function, fast twitch muscle activity, and muscle efficiency.

AGT (angiotensinogen) is an essential component of the renin-angiotensin system (RAS), a regulator of blood pressure, body fluid, and electrolyte homeostasis, and in athletic performance, blood pressure response to exercise.

HIF1A (hypoxia-inducible factor-1) is a transcription factor regulating several genes in response to hypoxic stimuli, specifically the generation of proteins involved in oxygen transport, glycolytic enzymes, and glucose transporters.

HIF1A (hypoxia-inducible factor-1) is a transcription factor regulating several genes in response to hypoxic stimuli, specifically the generation of proteins involved in oxygen transport, glycolytic enzymes, and glucose transporters.

PPARGC1A (peroxisome proliferator-activated receptor gamma, coactivator 1 alpha) is a transcriptional coactivator for steroid receptors and nuclear receptors which increases the activity of PPARG and thyroid hormone receptors. It regulates energy metabolism, mitochondrial biogenesis, thermogenesis, and skeletal muscle fiber-type conversion.

HNF4A (hepatocyte nuclear factor 4, alpha) is a transcription factor expressed in liver, intestine, pancreatic islets, and kidney. It regulates genes involved in lipid metabolism, insulin secretion, and glucose homeostasis.

HNF4A (hepatocyte nuclear factor 4, alpha) is a transcription factor expressed in liver, intestine, pancreatic islets, and kidney. It regulates genes involved in lipid metabolism, insulin secretion, and glucose homeostasis.

NAT2 (N-acetyltransferase 2) encodes an enzyme that is involved in carcinogen and drug metabolism. In athletic performance, this could translate into the ability to regulate ROS (reactive oxygen species) production and ROS-induced damage as high levels of ROS alter muscle contractility resulting in fatigue.
IL-1B (interleukin 1, beta) is a cytokine that is an important mediator of the inflammatory response, and active in skeletal muscle repair during and after exercise.
IL-1B (interleukin 1, beta) is a cytokine that is an important mediator of the inflammatory response, and active in skeletal muscle repair during and after exercise.

HFE (hereditary hemochromatosis protein) encodes a protein that associates with beta2-microglobulin. It controls iron absorption by regulating the interaction of the transferrin receptor with transferrin. The iron storage disorder, hereditary haemochromatosis, is a recessive genetic disorder that results from defects in this gene; in athletic performance, it is related to the ability to store iron without deleterious health effects.

HIF1A (hypoxia-inducible factor-1) is a transcription factor regulating several genes in response to hypoxic stimuli, specifically the generation of proteins involved in oxygen transport, glycolytic enzymes, and glucose transporters.
IGF1 (insulin-like growth factor 1) encodes proteins that are engaged in growth-promoting activity, particularly muscle growth and development.

MSTN GDF8 (myostatin, growth differentiation factor 8) encodes a protein that is a member of the bone morphogenetic protein (BMP) family and the TGF-beta superfamily. It acts as a negative regulator of skeletal muscle growth.

CREB1 (cAMP-responsive element-binding protein 1) expression influences heart rate response to regular exercise. A physically active individual can perform the same amount of physical work with less strain on the heart.

KIF5B (kinesin family member 5B) is related to the normal distribution of mitochondria and lysosomes. Changes in KIF5B expression alter mitochondrial localization and biogenesis in a manner that could affect the ability of the heart to adjust to regular exercise.
NOS3 (nitric oxide synthase 3) produces nitric oxide (NO), a biologic mediator associated with cardiovascular response to exertion and vascular smooth muscle relaxation.

NPY (neuropeptide Y) encodes a neuropeptide that is widely expressed in the central nervous system and influences cardiovascular function, including heart rate response to exercise and blood lipid concentrations.
ADRB1 (adrenergic beta-3 receptor) mediates epinephrine and norepinephrine which dilate air passages and are related to peak oxygen uptake and increased cardiac output.
APOE (apolipoprotein E) relates to oxygen-intake capacity and metabolic regulation through the binding and catabolism of lipoproteins.
APOE (apolipoprotein E) relates to oxygen-intake capacity and metabolic regulation through the binding and catabolism of lipoproteins.

NRF1 (nuclear respiratory factor 1) activates the expression of EIF2S1 which is related to respiration. Oxygen uptake and aerobic capacity is influenced through mitochondrial biogenesis and oxidative phosphorylation (ATP production) is increased.

NRF1 (nuclear respiratory factor 1) activates the expression of EIF2S1 which is related to respiration. Oxygen uptake and aerobic capacity is influenced through mitochondrial biogenesis and oxidative phosphorylation (ATP production) is increased.
AMPD1 (adenosine monophosphate deaminase 1) encodes an enzyme that regulates muscle glycolysis (ATP production and uptake) during exercise.
APOA1 (apolipoprotein A-I) is the major protein component of high density lipoprotein (HDL) in plasma. It binds and catabolizes lipoproteins from tissues to the liver for excretion.

PPARA (peroxisome proliferator-activated receptor alpha) is one of three subtypes (alpha, beta/delta, and gamma) of PPARs which affect the expression of genes related to cell proliferation and differentiation, and immune and inflammation responses. PPARA is involved in the regulation of liver, heart, and skeletal muscle lipid metabolism, fatty acid oxidation, and glucose homeostasis.

PPARD (peroxisome proliferator-activated receptor delta) is a second subtype of PPARs, and is involved in metabolic response including increases in fatty acid oxidation enzymes, mitochondrial biogenesis, and the production of contractile proteins.

PPARD (peroxisome proliferator-activated receptor delta) is a second subtype of PPARs, and is involved in metabolic response including increases in fatty acid oxidation enzymes, mitochondrial biogenesis, and the production of contractile proteins.

CKMM/CKM (creatine kinase, muscle) encodes an enzyme which is central to energy homeostasis and transduction in tissues with large, fluctuating energy demands like skeletal muscle, and is also implicated in skeletal muscle damage tolerance.

IL6 (interleukin 6 receptor) is a cytokine with a variety of functions including immune system response, cell growth and differentiation regulation, and inflammation and skeletal muscle repair activation. IL6 modulates changes in serum concentrations of high-density lipoprotein cholesterol (HDL) which influences recovery time in response to exercise.
DNAPTP6 (DNA polymerase-transactivated protein 6) is a stress granule and nucleolar protein related to willingness to train

PAPSS2 (3'-phosphoadenosine 5'-phosphosulfate synthase 2) encodes an enzyme with ATP sulfurylase and APS kinase activity that is involved in the sulfation of lipids, carbohydrates, and proteins and is widely expressed in skeletal and smooth muscles and the brain. PAPSS2 has been linked to maximal exercise capacity and it is proposed that exercise ability may be an important determinant of leisure time exercise behavior.
C18orf2 (chromosome 18 open reading frame 2) is an uncharacterized protein found to be related to willingness to train

CILP (cartilage intermediate layer protein) is involved in cartilage scaffolding. It is thought to act by suppressing IGF1-induced proliferation and sulfated proteoglycan synthesis, and by inhibiting TGFB1-mediated induction of cartilage matrix genes via its interaction with TGFB1.

COL1A1 (collagen type I, alpha 1) is a member of group I collagen (fibrillar forming collagen) and is found in most connective tissues, particularly bone, cornea, dermis, and tendon. Type I collagen is the major protein component of ligaments.
COL5A1 (collagen type V, alpha 1) is also a member of group I collagen. It is a minor connective tissue component used in the formation of tendon, ligament, bone, sclera, and cornea.

GDF5 (growth differentiation factor 5) encodes a protein that is a member of the bone morphogenetic protein (BMP) family and the TGF-beta superfamily. It is involved in bone formation and skeletal development and may enhance tendon repair and mechanical strength.
MMP3 (matrix metallopeptidase 3) is a protein that maintains extracellular matrix homeostasis by degrading fibronectin, laminin, collagens, and cartilage.
